column1: Between 25 October 2019 and 20 November 2019, how many candidates for the Democratic nomination for president of the United States will cease to be candidates?
column5: ['None', 'One or two', 'Three or four', 'Five or more']
column6: ['US Politics', 'Elections and Referenda']
Wow what a finish. In the last minute, Wayne Messam suspended his campaign, on Medium of all places, which is fitting for his shoelace operation.
I don't see 2 people withdrawing in the next 4 days.
This announcement may hasten one more out. Of COurse Bloomburg didn't make a ripple either.

Further proof that there are no smart Democrats left: Three more Maybes--Bloomberg, Clinton, and Patrick. The first one has some chance, the second is a bad joke, and the third has been struck with a bad case of messiah complex. So instead of losing three out of the clown car, they may add three.

dropping back on 3-4 I thought B;oomberg would enter but not a delyed start skipping Iowa and NH. So for now the field fights to still be alive till the convention Had he begun his campaign now the field would have winnowed.

I am revising my probability from 67 to 95 for only 1-2 to drop out. The reason is same as listed before and now it has gained more strength for may to stay. Also, many of them have received an auxiliary oxygen from impeachment process that reduces chances for 45 to remain and may help refresh the remaining field.

If Bloomberg comes in, there may be a race for the exits among the lesser lights. Bernie and Warren will stay in because they overestimate their personal magnificence, very much as The Current Incumbent does his. Biden will stay in because he feels entitled to the nomination, although his support will vanish as the dew at midday since presumed electability is his only asset and Bloomberg has him beat on that dimension from Day One. Klobuchar will stay in but only to get the nod for VP, which by the way would be an excellent choice for Bloomberg. Buttigieg will stay in untiil either he or his True Believers catch on that he is actually less qualified than Sarah Palin. Some but not all of the loonies will stay in for a while longer, but enough may bail out that I'm bumping the "5 or more" up to 1%.

I've run a monte carlo simulation using the year to date and distribution of drop out dates for the 11 candidates who've left the campaign to today, and I get an 83.2% probability of no more drop outs, 12.3% chance of 1 more, 3.3% chance of 2 and 1.3% chance of 3 with no occurrences of 4 or more in 2000 trials.
updating with only 1 days left to go, still only one has dropped out.

Other than Castro, not seeing any other candidate dropping out. I may have overestimated the impact of the drop out of a "star" (O'Rourke) on other candidates.
Update for small passage of time.
Shifting to One or two since Beto dropped out.
Castro is changing strategy and pivoting hard toward Iowa [1], which suggests to me that his chances of dropping out in the near future are lower, as he'd want to see how his new Iowa bid plays out.

Again I used the candidates' travel to Iowa and NH [1] as a gauge of how committed the candidates are to continue the presidential nomination contest. It is unlikely that the nine candidates that qualified for the November debate to drop out.

My previous update today didn't take proper consideration of the probabilities. There's a good chance of either 0 or 1 new withdrawals over the next 20 days, but also a relatively decent chance of more than 1. I feel like I'm still erring a bit too much in favour of 1 or 2, and that the chances of > 2 are higher than 25%, but at the same time I find myself gaming the system in my head and being influenced by self-talk... :-)

Updating to reflect the passage of time and one withdrawal so far (Beta O'Rourke). This year so far, 11 candidates have withdrawn, or about one per month, so the most likely occurrence over the next 20 days is 2/3 of another withdrawal.

Castro reportedly raised 90% of his “do or die” (too much Brexit news you say?) fundraising goal by the morning of Oct 31. Maybe last minute donations even got him above the target by the end of the day. He also just got a flattering profile in Time. I am guessing those two factors forestall his drop out in the short term.

The first few times this question was asked, I carefully weighed each candidate to evaluate their polling, financial position, and path forward. I then watched as far fewer candidates than predicted dropped out and realized I forgot to account for the ego a person who thinks they can run for president .
Only nine candidates have qualified for the November debate so far, and perhaps only one or two more will qualify by the Nov 13 deadline.

It all comes down to how expensive these campaigns are and how successful (or not) each candidate is at getting funds. Julian Castro has already indicated that needs to raise money by the end of the month or will need to drop out. Also, Joe Biden, Elizabeth Warren, Pete Buttigieg, and Bernie Sanders have all far out paced other candidates in terms of raising campaign funds. I think it's likely that at least one candidate or possibly two will withdraw.
